• AR Cards: Interactive cards that bring artifacts to life with additional information, animations,
and 3D models.
• User Navigation: Free movement in VR spaces with guided tours highlighting significant
events, leaders, and cultural practices.
The platform is designed for both educational and recreational use, providing an engaging
environment where students can explore history, ask questions, and experience national heritage
interactively. Its structure allows for continuous updates and expansions, making RuhVR a dynamic
tool for cultural education and preservation.
II RESEARCH SECTION
2.1 Research and Applied Technologies
Analytical Overview of Known Results:
Over the past decade, virtual reality (VR) and augmented reality (AR) have become widely
applied in education to enhance student engagement. International projects such as Google
Expeditions, TimeLooper, and other virtual museums have shown that immersive experiences
significantly improve retention, comprehension, and motivation among learners. However, these
platforms rarely provide content in minority or local languages, and none focus specifically on
Kazakh history or culture. Existing research confirms that interactive and experiential learning
promotes deeper understanding compared to traditional textbook-based methods [1][2].
Applied Technologies:
RuhVR integrates several modern technologies:
• VR (Virtual Reality): Allows students to explore 3D historical environments.
• AR (Augmented Reality): Enhances learning through interactive cards that display artifacts
in 3D when scanned with a smartphone.
• AI (Artificial Intelligence): Supports adaptive navigation and user interaction, such as
highlighting key historical events or guiding the user through exhibits.
• 3D Modeling Software: Unity and LiveHome 3D Pro are used to create realistic artifacts and
environments.
2.2 Technical Implementation of the RuhVR Virtual Museum
System Architecture:
The platform is composed of three main modules:
1. 2. Content Module: Includes 3D models of historical artifacts, buildings, traditional clothing,
and cultural scenes.
VR Interface: Provides navigation within different historical eras, from the Stone Age to
Independent Kazakhstan.
5
3. AR Module: Interactive cards allow users to access additional information, animations, and
3D objects.
Implementation Steps:
• Research and selection of historically accurate references and sources.
• Development of 3D assets for artifacts, landscapes, and interiors.
• Integration of VR environments with AR features.
• Testing in school classrooms with students from grades 7–9 to collect feedback on usability
and engagement.
• Optimization of content for smooth performance on commonly available VR devices.
Observations:
During testing, most students were able to navigate the virtual museum intuitively. Teachers
reported that the platform encouraged discussion, questions, and active participation. Users were
especially engaged by the AR cards that visualized rare artifacts in 3D [3].
2.3 Content and Structure
Content Overview:
The virtual museum contains several historical eras, each with its own section:
• Stone Age and Early Settlers: Artifacts, tools, and 3D reconstructions of settlements.
User Interaction:
• Users can move freely in VR environments.
• Clicking on artifacts provides detailed descriptions, historical context, and multimedia
content.
• AR cards trigger animations, 3D reconstructions, and supplementary data.
Illustrations:
• Graphs and charts show engagement levels and test results.
• Screenshots of VR interfaces highlight navigation and interactivity.
• Diagrams explain system architecture and workflow.
Results and Discussion
• Educational Impact: After testing, 70% of participants reported increased interest in history.
• User Engagement: The interactive features and immersive experience significantly enhanced
comprehension and retention of historical facts.
• Teacher Feedback: RuhVR is suitable as a supplementary educational tool. It promotes
independent exploration and discussion among students.6
• Technical Insights: The VR platform runs smoothly on standard VR headsets; AR integration
increases the interactivity and memorability of artifacts.
Conclusion of Research Section:
RuhVR demonstrates that combining VR, AR, and AI in education can create an engaging,
culturally relevant, and effective learning environment. This project provides a practical model for
future educational applications focused on national heritage and history [4][5].
Live Home 3D Pro
To design the architectural layout of the virtual museum’s interior, the Live Home 3D Pro software
was used. This tool allowed precise modeling of exhibition halls, including the placement of walls,
lighting direction, movement trajectories, and the visitor’s virtual navigation within the space.
Each room is dedicated to a specific historical era, providing a clear and immersive chronological
journey. For example:
• Stone Age Hall: displays early settlements, tools, and artifacts.
The software enabled realistic visualization of the museum environment, ensuring that users could
freely explore each era while maintaining historical accuracy and spatial coherence.
7
PanoTour
To create 360° panoramic views and a fully immersive exploration experience, the PanoTour
platform was utilized. This tool allows users to navigate exhibition halls from any angle and zoom
in on individual artifacts.
This feature enhances the “full immersion effect” of RuhVR, providing users with a realistic
feeling of being present in a physical museum. By combining panoramic navigation with interactive
elements, visitors can explore every detail of the exhibits, increasing engagement and fostering a
deeper understanding of historical objects and environments.
8
3D Models and Sources
• The 3D models of museum exhibits were collected and created using Blender, Sketchfab,
CGTrader, and other open-access resources. Some artifacts—such as Bronze Age pottery
and the weapons of Kazakh warriors—were reconstructed based on archaeological sketches
and illustrations from historical publications. All models were refined and adapted in terms
of scale and texture for seamless integration into the Unity environment.
RuhVR Museum Structure
• The virtual museum consists of several key sections:
• Introduction Hall: An animated scene introducing the project’s purpose and concept.
• Historical Eras: Six main halls covering periods from the Stone Age to Modern Kazakhstan.
Each hall provides an immersive exploration of cultural artifacts, architecture, and historical
context.
• Interactive Cards: Each exhibit includes a digital card with the artifact’s name, era,
discovery location, and cultural significance. Users can access these cards to gain additional
information in 3D.
• Audio Support: Each hall features atmospheric sounds and traditional music to enhance
immersion and create a realistic museum experience.
• This combination of 3D modeling, interactive elements, and audio-visual cues ensures that
users can engage fully with the museum, explore artifacts in detail, and experience Kazakh
history in an interactive and memorable way.
